Image source: Denis Ismagilov – 123RF.comAmong the observations, Brenda Bensted-Smith, owner of Ad Talent says, "We have seen more digital, more tech, more remote working, more contract employment and more global engagement."Key observations: There was not much movement with regards to salary in 2022, except in tech and senior creative positions There was a seismic shift in employer, employee relationships and working environments In line with our 2021 survey, there is a continuing trend towards hiring on freelance, contract or short-term permanent basis with employers justifying this strategy by saying they are only dealing with tangible business in front of them Hiring on contract with a view to go permanent is a common brief for us Job descriptions became more blurred with hybrid skills high on the list of 'must haves' in the brief to us Employers are demanding more work for the same pay. This doesn’t reflect in our survey as salary categories are quite binary and categorised into specific job descriptions Despite the increase in opportunities in Cape Town and an increase in remote working the remuneration gap between Johannesburg and Cape Town is still evident Remuneration in the tech space between the Johannesburg and Cape Town has closed and we have seen no difference between the two cities in most tech categories We noticed an increase of approximately 10% in senior creatives The difference between Johannesburg and Cape Town at junior to mid-level is significant at up to 20% in some categories The “Events” category makes a comeback this year after missing the last two years because of Covid Skilled candidates remain in high demand and their demands have shifted from strong financial rewards to flexibility around working hours and remote working. Lifestyle is a key factor for many when deciding to advance their careers Sought-after skills such as social media and tech roles are well rewarded Many candidates say they have taken on side hustles to make ends meet The global workspace is open for South Africans and there are increasing opportunities for local talent to play on the world stage The financial impact of Covid is still very evident and both employers and candidates are wary of risk We have seen more counter-offers from employers upon resignation in 2022 than in any other year. Most counter-offers arise when employees resign because they want flexible work from home arrangements which the employer then grants Skilled candidates are in demand and they know it!Survey parametersThis survey was compiled: using figures of actual placements made by Ad Talent using figures from salary information obtained from all candidates interviewed by Ad Talent from January 2022 to December 2022 using figures from salary information obtained from candidates who have submitted their CVs to Ad Talent using cost to company (CTC) figures using the average salaries per sectorInterpretation: Salaries vary significantly depending on many factors, including size of the company, desirability to work for a particular company and status Salaries for media sales roles vary significantly depending on the commission structure / incentives 0-2 years (light) means 0 to 2 years experience in that particular position and NOT 0 to 2 years total working experience The same applies for medium and heavy weight. It is experience in the particular position and NOT total working experience This survey is not intended to be prescriptive, but is a report on what Ad Talent, (not the entire industry) has experienced in the past 12 monthsAdvertising0-2 yrs (light)2 – 5 yrs (medium)5 – 9 yrs (heavyweight)Managing DirectorJohannesburgR90 000 – R100 000R100 000 – R150 000R150 000+Cape TownR75 000 – R90 000R90 000 – R130 000R130 000+Deputy MDJohannesburgR85 000 – R94 000R94 000 – R100 000R100 000+Cape TownR75 000 – R84 000R84 000 – R93 000R93 000+Client Service/Business Unit DirectorJohannesburgR56 000 – R60 000R60 000 – R66 000R66 000+Cape TownR48 000 – R55 000R55 